Esa decides on major space missions: missions for billions
Far-off planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to start in the coming years.
30 proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far worlds.
More than 1000 planets on other stars have already found astronomers.
No one knows if there are lives on at least some of them.
The selection is difficult: do you want to look for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or have you been looking for Earth-like planets and perhaps discover alien life?
These questions are being raised by the European Space Agency, Esa.
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects to make research a major contribution.
The budget for such "L-missions" is about one billion euros each.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were the subject of debate, five of which have now come to the closer choice.
A large number of bodies review the proposals and follow up with the researchers.
In the next few days a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by the Esa, to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme launched in 2007 will find answers.
What are the conditions for the creation of planets and lives?
The exact processes of the creation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also of planets that surround these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this dark.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to address this question, the space telescope "Cheops" will be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems will be examined in more detail in our near environment.
The possibilities are limited, however, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, the astronomers could depict earth-like planets and even analyse the composition of their atmospheres and thus look for "biomarkers": gases that are considered as an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is intended to provide an overview of the conditions for the creation of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation it causes with the planet system play an important role.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined in an exemplary way.
With the "Solar Orbiter," the Esa has already approved a M-Class mission (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe is to start in 2017 and closely monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
The researchers are also of great interest to Jupiter and his moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa provides the first of the three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme.
The Juice probe (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to start its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, she reaches Jupiter and is to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moon of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and to study whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
It may also be possible to find differences that could lead the physicists to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos were created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, which consists of stars, planets and living beings as we are, there are dark matter, whose gravity holds together galaxies and galaxies, and dark energy, through which the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know what physical laws were valid in the first few seconds of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid," the Esa has already approved a M mission here, which is scheduled to start in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky and thus allow for conclusions on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will be left at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts "E-Lisa," the best chance of obtaining an L-mission is a demanding concept for the detection of gravitational waves.
These include changes in the structure of space time, which Albert Einstein had predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been shown to this day.
Elisa could do this, hoping the scientists behind the project.
The mission provides for a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
Unlike plants on Earth, it could also demonstrate gravitational waves that were created during the Big Bang and thus provide new insights about the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena," which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets," another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism," a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder," which is to detect and investigate earth-like planets.
There are already proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics.
