What happens on the way with my e-mail?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
When designing the Internet service, has e-mail been technically implemented in the same way as the traditional mail?
In the design of the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not been taken into account to create a stable basis for a hearing-safe exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends a mail to "Benni," are the computers of the two connected directly?
The email program or the browser of Anna sends the mail to the mail server of her service provider in the first step.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
On the route the mail can run via a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Are conventional e-mails read through the network on their way?
Most of the mails are read several times by software robots on the way.
At the provider of the sender, it is usually checked whether the mail carries a malicious program as an annex.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is a troublesome and unwanted spam mail that is deleted immediately or at least sorted out into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
In systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their coming holiday trip, Google can display appropriate links to holiday offers.
