Pfandhuizen booming in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawn house in the Bendemee shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay the school fees of her daughters.
"My husband and I just bought a house, there's all my money in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she made $3,000 every month (about €1,730) as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
Indeed, demand in parts of South-East Asia - where the debt of households is increasing - is so high that ValueMax, where she has made her exchange, became the third pawn house listed on the Singapurian stock exchange this week.
The pledge of jewelry is not only a fast way to get money - 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga - but also almost as favourable as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, Pfandhuizen in Singapore requires an effective annual rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent that the United Overseas Bank requires, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping centre.
However, Pfandhuizen offers the advantage that there is no need to review the creditworthiness or evidence of income, which is why loans are possible faster than in banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawnhouses after families feel the pressure of increasing living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a more relaxed fiscal policy in the developed economies, families with lower and medium income are looking for pawnhouses to balance the difference with stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's growing budgetary debt, mainly through increasing mortgages, was described as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
The Agency considers that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest budgetary debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80% of GDP, an increase of 60% still in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which has just come out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a decline in consumer demand.
"In the end, this means that, given increasing costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical ceilings in gold prices in the last two years have increased the trend towards the union of personal objects, as people use the opportunity to turn the family's jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the committed items are gold in the 200 pawn houses in the city state.
People say, "The gold price looks good, let's get Grandmother's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20% increase in customers in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the pawn business is so strong that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighbouring Malaysia - where the company operates four houses - but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it received this week with the Singapore stock exchange.
While some lenders were in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah, it explains that Pfandhuizen not only offered more favourable interest than other lenders, but also did not directly increase the debt.
"Customers insult items they already own, and the liquid personal property does not increase the budgetary debt," she explains.
The lending business is increasingly socially accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Nor are all people using pawnings in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to the ValueMax branch to fund gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Our customers come to us from every social shift.
"These include well-being, who borrow something for a business or an investment in the short term, or small companies that need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow," says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
