From departure to landing, passengers can now use their electronic equipment to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but do not call with their phone, according to the new guidelines published by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
As soon as they were implemented, depending on the airline, FAA staff Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new directives and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight crew and the rules for the storage of the equipment in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to develop the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could very soon approve the extended use of electronic devices," the FAA announced in a release.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
You may not start it again until the plane has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives green light.
When entering the landing approach, passengers will have to turn them off again and they will not be allowed to start again until the plane has landed.
According to the new directives, airlines whose aircraft were secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the equipment even when they were launched, landing and on the rolling field, said the FAA.
Most of the new aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to larger heights for the use of Wi-Fi should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the professional association of professional flight crew members, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regulation is safely implemented - and we work closely with the airline in this respect - both sides will benefit from it," commented Glading.
We are, to be honest, tired of having to feel like a caregiver on this subject.
However, Internet connections to surf, exchange e-mails, text messages or download data under three kilometres were still prohibited, the Authority explained.
Passengers are invited to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave a jet of American Airlines effectively because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the sidewalk.
And more heavy devices such as laptops must continue to be stored because there is a risk of injury in case they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone calls during the flight will continue to be prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may remove a ban on certain electronic devices at start-up and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transport Safety Board, said security experts on national transport issues on CBS News, mobile phones would still be considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could cause potential disturbances in navigation equipment, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission masts," Rosenker said.
A consulting committee of the industry, set up by the FAA to examine this issue, recommended last month that the government should allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as the democratic senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri are of the opinion that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the equipment has become omnipresent.
In some studies it is said that up to one third of passengers forget or ignore the switch-off of the device.
The FAA started to limit the use of electronic equipment by passengers in 1966, after reports of disturbances of navigation and communication equipment by the VHF radio carried by passengers, which were the latest technical trend at the time.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they do not make any electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing Wi-Fi to passengers for a few years when the height of the flight is reached.
The planes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the increased use of electronic equipment under the new directives, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally provide much less radio than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only give out minimal radiation when you are being overturned.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the supporters of a relaxation of the restrictions on the use of equipment by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees invited a passenger aircraft full of Kindle E-Reader and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not find any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the Passenger Association National Association of Airline Passengers said he felt that the interference from the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there are only isolated reports of pilots who speak for a malfunction of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them are very old.
The Committee, however, recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the shutdown of the equipment by passengers in the event of an instrument landing under bad conditions of vision.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and called them a reasonable adjustment for travellers who would now be fully equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognises that a pleasant passenger experience is not in conflict with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
