Scientists were able to shed more light on the context in which a dog's swallowing is associated with his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tail waved more to the right (from the point of view of the dog), while it was the left side of nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and react to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it is well known that the left and right half of the brain react differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the side tail of their fellow species, the researchers are monitoring the animals while these movies were looking at other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged and analysed the behaviour.
Probably soon we'll understand why the tail is moving in one direction, in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said: "We have shown the dogs to films with dogs - either a natural version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we have thus been able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or to the right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressive dog moving his tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail-tilt was primarily left (again from the perspective of the dog that wanders), their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
He is rather convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said, "If you have different encounters with other dogs and the weaving with the tail in one direction is more connected with friendly behavior and the right side produces more of a less friendly behavior, then you respond on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their animal's emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and guest scholarship at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine whether the dog was important to the left and right.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found out that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it's a satisfied dog.
In another research work at the University of Victoria in Canada, the following was said: "Dogs go more towards a robot dog when they are" tail "waving left and not right, rather than getting restless - just the other way around than in the Italian study."
According to his statement, the differences could therefore be that in the various studies the dogs did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
"Although there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined - and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
