Pope Francis appointed first Cardinals in February
Pope Francis will be called new Cardinals of the Catholic Church on 22 February, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope and they are also the ones who choose a Pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached an age of 80 can no longer take part in the Pope's election - that is to say, a group of 120 "elected cardinals."
In a statement in which the news was announced, Father Federico Lombardi, a speaker of the Vatican, said that a meeting of all the cardinals would take place before the ceremony was held to appoint the new cardinals, which is also known as the Consistorium.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the Consistency in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned," said Lombardi.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that the number of elected cardinals will probably have fallen by February.
He said that a Pope would normally appoint as many cardinals as necessary, so that the number of eligible cardinals would be 120 again, and as many cardinals over 80 as he would like.
The consistency next year was important because it was the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
At the moment there has been a certain overhang on Europe's sides, and in particular Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore the balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they only have a small number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world who have the task of finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
"Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," said Valero.
He said it was "well possible" that Francis asked the Cardinals for advice.
But so far we have not been in this situation - all of this is completely new.
