On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Blou brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwave and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Choose here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 of the "CNN Heroes of 2013."
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him as the "CNN Hero of the Year."
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father lose consciousness and travel to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Blou was injured in 1981 in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation, which spread to his brain and caused a hematoma that should affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," says Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years with his father in overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5: 00 in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and it's not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwell's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people each, according to the World Health Organisation.
On the other hand, the relationship in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for her, most camerunas could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and almost three quarters of the country's health expenditure is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his fellow countrymen suffer in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team carried out 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organisation called ASCOVIME, which travels on weekends in rural areas and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people forced themselves into small buses and went to the villages that need help with the severed medical equipment on the roof over unfixed terrain.
It's not always going smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be received as heroes: a feast, singing and dance, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and wave - with its wide smile and its limitless energy - is happy to join the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team will start investigating hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village - and this is on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others get crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document that is required for the school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, city hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next person.
The lighting for the surgery and the disinfectant is fed by the generator of the group, so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It's a hard pensum, but the village musicians usually help to keep the team motivated.
"They'll be drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," says Blou.
On Sunday the team then goes back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group - a mixture of Cameroon's doctors and foreign medical students - carried out 700 free operations last year and knows that with its work it makes a huge difference for the people to whom it helps.
A man explained that the free operation of a lesion that he had received now allowed him to work again.
"This changes the future of my family," said the man.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activities, according to Bwelle; the rest come from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and is working in Bwell's group on a voluntary basis.
He's always in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students such as O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support the wave, this is an opportunity to gain practical experiences that they would never get at home.
"We can be involved in operations where we help to tap blood or keep the instruments for Dr. Blou," explains O'Malley.
That would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and bring often donated health care material.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, the transport and the instructions.
"He is no doubt a hero," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon knows no limits.
The almost constant work is not a burden for the wave.
To help others to live a happier life and to fulfil a promise he has given to his Father is a great joy to him.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," says Bwelle.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
